{"questionId":"22226319","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Jerry sells the perfect chocolates for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>50</mn></math> pesos each and the flawed ones for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>15</mn></math> pesos each.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Calculate the expected number of pesos Jerry makes from selling a batch of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>20</mn></math> randomly selected chocolates.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>either one of two terms in expected value formula correct&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>50</mn><mfenced><mrow><mn>20</mn><mfenced><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>96</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mn>15</mn><mfenced><mrow><mn>20</mn><mfenced><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>04</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow></mfenced></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>972</mn></math>&nbsp;(pesos)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:right;\"><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"22226319","referenceCode":"24M.1.SL.TZ2.6b","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Calculate the expected number of pesos Jerry makes from selling a batch of 20 randomly selected chocolates.","paper":"1","level":"SL","questionNumber":"b","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 4—Statistics and probability","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","SL 4.7—Discrete random variables"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}